{
  "doc_id": "50499",
  "text": "A critical component in eliciting and sustaining the angiogenic phenotype of tumors is hypoxia. [CITATION_1] Heterogeneity in oxygenation is a constant feature of the tumor microenvironment as neoplastic vasculature development cannot keep up with the metabolic demands of proliferating tumor cells, resulting in an architecturally and functionally compromised vasculature. The hypoxic microenvironment of melanomas is associated with tumor progression and metastatic dissemination [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and serves as a stimulus for the induction of several pro-angiogenic modulators. Endothelial cells (ECs) are known to undergo cell death in response to adverse stimuli such as hypoxia. [CITATION_4] As EC survival is a crucial step in the angiogenic cascade, we sought to evaluate the angiogenic potential of melanoma cell lines, differing in their degree of aggressiveness and clinical staging, [CITATION_5] by investigating their ability to mediate EC survival under restrictive culture conditions.",
